{
  "doc_id": "22488",
  "text": "Since the uptake of amino acids across the plasma membrane is known to be mediated in part by protoncoupled cotransporter systems [CITATION_1] , it is likely that aha2 mutants have a reduced uptake of amino acids. Many amino acids externally supplied at high concentrations cause growth retardation in Arabidopsis seedlings [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , possibly by creating metabolic imbalances detrimental to growth. Thus, we predicted that there would be differential growth responses between the wild type and aha2 mutants exposed to high concentrations of amino acids in the growth medium. We first optimized the concentration of each amino acid by finding the concentrations that induced 20% to 80% inhibition in wild-type plants compared with control conditions (one-half-strength MS medium, 1% [w/v] Suc at pH 5.7; Supplemental  Fig. S2) . The concentration at which a particular amino acid was effective varied, possibly due to differences in the transport and/or catabolic mechanisms for each amino acid or to the endogenous concentrations of those amino acids in Arabidopsis seedlings, as documented by [CITATION_5] . From these results, we chose the appropriate amino acid concentrations to compare the differential growth responses of the wild type and aha2 mutants.",
